# Drug Offences Examples
{"prompt": "Query: What is the maximum sentence for drug trafficking of 15 grams of heroin?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Under the Misuse of Drugs Act (MDA) s 5, trafficking heroin carries a maximum sentence of life imprisonment and a fine up to $500,000. Trafficking more than 15g typically falls within the enhanced trafficking framework under MDA s 33B. The court will assess: (1) quantity and purity; (2) street value vs. pure form; (3) whether the offender played a significant role in the operation. See Suvendu Prasad Chatterjee v Public Prosecutor [2020] 2 SLR 740 for sentencing benchmarks. Mandatory death penalty applies only for quantities exceeding 15g in certain jurisdictions depending on purity."}

{"prompt": "Query: What are the key defences to drug trafficking charges?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Key defences to drug trafficking under MDA s 5 include: (1) Knowledge - the offender must have known the substance was a drug; (2) Possession for purpose - trafficking requires intention to distribute, not mere possession; (3) Safety valve under MDA s 33B - if the offender proves they provided substantial assistance to the Central Narcotics Bureau; (4) Entrapment - law enforcement inducement can vitiate the charge; (5) Causation - proving the offender directly caused the trafficking. See Aziz s/o Abdul Kadir v Public Prosecutor [2015] 1 SLR 1039 for the substantial assistance framework. Possession alone is insufficient; the prosecution must establish trafficking intent."}

{"prompt": "Query: What factors does the court consider in sentencing for drug offences?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " In sentencing for drug offences, courts under the MDA s 33 consider: (1) Quantity - crystal clear benchmark: trafficking 15-30g = 20-30 years; (2) Purity and conversion to pure weight; (3) Role of offender - supplier vs. courier (lower culpability); (4) Street value and profit potential; (5) International involvement (aggravating); (6) Cooperation with authorities under s 33B (mitigating); (7) Antecedents and character; (8) Personal circumstances (financial hardship, family obligations). See Vasentha d/o Joseph v Public Prosecutor [2015] 2 SLR 214 for the sentencing framework. Courts follow a 'two-step' approach: establish the starting point based on quantity/purity, then adjust for aggravating/mitigating factors."}

# Sexual Offences Examples  
{"prompt": "Query: What is the definition of rape under Singapore law and what are the elements?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Rape under the Penal Code s 375 requires proof of: (1) Sexual penetration by the penis into the vagina, anus, or mouth; (2) Without consent; (3) Against the victim's will or knowledge (MPC s 375(2)); (4) Mens rea - knowledge or rashness as to the lack of consent. Key case: R v Ng Gek Poh (1979-1980) SLR 144 established the 'no consent' principle. Consent must be: freely and voluntarily given, without duress/threat/intimidation, and must exist at the time of the act. Intoxication of the victim does not automatically negate consent if she can still communicate her wishes. See R v Bree [2007] 2 WLR 507 (English law, persuasive authority in SG) - even intoxicated victims can consent if they retain sufficient capacity to decide."}

{"prompt": "Query: What defences are available for a charge of sexual assault by penetration (s 376 PC)?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Defences to sexual assault by penetration (Penal Code s 376) include: (1) Consent - genuine voluntary agreement without coercion; mistake of fact as to consent (reasonable belief); (2) Identity - offender was not the perpetrator; (3) Automatism - involuntary physical act without conscious control; (4) Duress - offence committed under threats of death/grievous injury; (5) Insanity - lacking capacity to form mens rea; (6) Honest/reasonable mistake of fact - reasonable belief that victim consented or was above age of consent. The burden of proving consent defence lies on the defence, not the prosecution (s 376(3) PC). However, the prosecution bears the burden of proving lack of consent beyond reasonable doubt. See Public Prosecutor v Goh Han Heng [2012] 4 SLR 1087 on the intoxication state necessary to vitiate consent."}

# Sentencing Examples
{"prompt": "Query: What is the sentencing framework for culpable homicide (not amounting to murder)?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Culpable homicide under Penal Code s 299 (causing death by rash/negligent act) carries imprisonment up to 3 years, fine up to $1,000, or both. Sentencing frameworks: (1) Rash act (higher culpability) - 18-36 months imprisonment depending on dangerousness; (2) Negligent act (lower culpability) - 6-18 months. Court considers: degree of recklessness, severity of injury risk, number of victims affected. See Public Prosecutor v Kwong Kok Boon [2020] 4 SLR 1187 for sentencing guidelines. Aggravating factors: intoxication, high-speed driving, ignoring safety warnings. Mitigating factors: genuine remorse, confession, first offender, cooperation with authorities. Mandatory minimum is 6 months in certain circumstances (e.g., caused death while driving under influence)."}

# Criminal Procedure Examples
{"prompt": "Query: What is the difference between criminal revision and criminal reference under the CPC 2010?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Under the Criminal Procedure Code 2010: (1) Criminal Revision (s 400) - ANY person can apply for review of conviction/sentence where there is gross miscarriage of justice or procedural irregularity. The High Court can set aside conviction, order retrial, or vary sentence. Used for serious procedural breaches or fresh evidence. (2) Criminal Reference (s 397) - ONLY the Public Prosecutor can refer questions of law of public importance from acquittals to the High Court (does not overturn acquittal itself). Used to clarify law for future cases. (3) Criminal Appeal (s 377) - the CONVICTED person appeals directly to High Court within 14 days of sentence (as of right). See Public Prosecutor v Koh Thiam Huat [2017] 4 SLR 1099 on revisional powers. Criminal revision requires showing 'grave injustice' standard, much higher than ordinary appeals."}

# Violent Crimes Examples
{"prompt": "Query: What elements must be proven to convict someone of voluntarily causing grievous hurt (s 325 PC)?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Voluntarily causing grievous hurt under Penal Code s 325 requires proof of: (1) Act - the accused voluntarily caused hurt; (2) Grievous hurt - 8 types specified in s 320 PC: emasculation, permanent privation of limb/sight/power, acid burns >20% body surface, fractures, dislocation, tooth loss >3 teeth, inability to follow ordinary occupations >20 days; (3) Mens rea - intent or knowledge that act is likely to cause grievous hurt. The prosecution must prove the injury meets the legal threshold of 'grievous' not merely 'simple' hurt. See Seah Lay Hock v Public Prosecutor [2014] 2 SLR 123 for the distinction between simple and grievous hurt. Defences: private defence (s 99-106 PC), provocation, diminished responsibility, automatism. Punishment: imprisonment up to 10 years and/or fine up to $10,000."}

# Property Crimes Examples
{"prompt": "Query: What is the crime of cheating under Singapore law (PCA s 417) and what elements must be proven?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Cheating under the Penal Code s 417 requires: (1) Dishonest inducement - intentionally deceiving or attempting to deceive; (2) With intent causing person to act/omit in manner prejudicial to their interest; (3) Delivery of property/money or signing/stamping/producing document. The deception can be by misrepresentation, concealment, or abuse of position. The victim must actually be deceived and act on that deception. See Chua Kian Kok v Public Prosecutor [1999] 4 SLR 772 for the dishonest inducement standard. Punishment: imprisonment up to 10 years and/or fine up to $50,000. Cheating by personation (s 419) - pretending to be another person - carries enhanced punishment: imprisonment up to 20 years and/or fine up to $100,000. The prosecution must prove the offender knew their acts were dishonest or reckless as to whether they were dishonest."}

# Regulatory Examples
{"prompt": "Query: What constitutes drink driving under the Road Traffic Act and what are the penalties?\n\nAnswer:", "response": " Drink driving under the Road Traffic Act (RTA) s 67 is driving with breath alcohol >0.35mg/100ml OR blood alcohol >0.80mg/100ml. Penalties: (1) First offence - fine $1,000-$5,000, imprisonment up to 6 months; (2) Second offence - fine $3,000-$10,000, imprisonment up to 12 months; (3) Third+ offence - fine $5,000-$20,000, imprisonment up to 3 years. Mandatory disqualification: minimum 1 year (first), 3 years (second), 5 years (third+). Enhanced penalties if: caused accident/injury, high alcohol level (>0.80mg), during night hours, in residential areas. See Heng Keng Low v Public Prosecutor [2012] 3 SLR 450. Defence: medical condition affecting breathalyzer reading. Refusing breath test carries same penalties as testing positive."}

